    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "682d451d_ff472e0b",
        "filename": "src/core/SkReadBuffer.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 401,
      "author": {
        "id": 7830
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-16T00:17:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e No way, volatile does not help you here, and if an untrusted process is able to change this buffer while it\u0027s being read in a trusted process, I think I\u0027m back to the position that I\u0027d like you to excise Skia completely from any cross-process communication you\u0027re doing.\n\nThat will basically mean we copy anything passed to skia into local memory first. And that\u0027s a lot of allocation/copying for many data types (SkTextBlobs, SkPaths, SkFlattenables). We could maybe do something like use scratch buffers to avoid the reallocations but I don\u0027t follow why its difficult to have skia consider this deserialization a security boundary and structure it with that in mind. We had to do that for cc/paint deserialization, I\u0027m not following what\u0027s different about skia..?",
      "parentUuid": "75bdef34_65be6217",
